  abstract = {This article examines three candidate cases of non-causal explanation in computational neuroscience. I argue that there are instances of efficient coding explanation that are strongly analogous to examples of non-causal explanation in physics and biology, as presented by Batterman ([2002]), Woodward ([2003]), and Lange ([2013]). By integrating Lange's and Woodward's accounts, I offer a new way to elucidate the distinction between causal and non-causal explanation, and to address concerns about the explanatory sufficiency of non-mechanistic models in neuroscience. I also use this framework to shed light on the dispute over the interpretation of dynamical models of the brain. 1{$\quad$}Introduction 1.1{$\quad$}Efficient coding explanation in computational neuroscience 1.2{$\quad$}Defining non-causal explanation 2{$\quad$}Case I: Hybrid Computation 3{$\quad$}Case II: The Gabor Model Revisited 4{$\quad$}Case III: A Dynamical Model of Prefrontal Cortex 4.1{$\quad$}A new explanation of context-dependent computation 4.2{$\quad$}Causal or non-causal? 5{$\quad$}Causal and Non-causal: Does the Difference Matter?}
